The dataset consists of n=2378 capture observations across different islands in the house sparrow meta-population. These data are in what is known as ‘long format’, with individuals appearing in multiple rows representing each occasion they were captured. First a bit of simple data exploration:

##     Gjeroy Hestmannoy     Kvaroy      Myken 
##        571       1353        337        117

marked requires capture histories to be in ‘wide’ format, with each row representing one individual. The capture history forms a string of 1s and 0s with no spaces, with a 1 for each capture or sighting and a 0 when an individual wasn’t detected. All histories should have the same number of entries and therefore be the same length. They should appear in the first column of the dataframe which must be named ‘ch’. The following code uses pipes (%>%) and the spread(), unite() and group_by() functions from the tidyr and dplyr packages to generate the appropriate format.

temp <- longdata[,1:2] # take the first two columns, id and year and put into a temporary dataframe
temp$detect <- 1 # add column for detection (all 1s because these represent captures) 

temp <- temp %>%
  # remove duplicates, which may occur when individuals are caught multiple times in an sampling event
  distinct() %>%
  # spread out data. The fill = 0 adds rows for combinations of id and year where individuals were not observed
  spread(year, detect, fill = 0) %>% 
  # for every individual....
  group_by(id) %>%
  # paste together 0's and 1's using unite()
  # here we are pasting the strings together from the second column (first capture event)
  # to the last capture event ("tail(names(.),1)")
  # use sep="" so there are no characters separating 0's and 1's
  unite("ch", 2:tail(names(.),1), sep = "")

sparrow <- as.data.frame(temp) # new dataframe called sparrow
head(sparrow)
##    id         ch
## 1   1 0000100100
## 2  14 0001000000
## 3  18 1000000000
## 4  24 0000001000
## 5  57 0000001000
## 6 100 0000100000

We are now ready to run a simple Capture-Mark-Recapture analysis.

Simple Cormack-Jolly-Seber model

A CJS model estimates apparent survival (Phi) and detection probability (p) for open populations. Each of these is a linear model on the logit scale (bound between 0 and 1). This is the same transformation or ‘link function’ used in a binomial Generalised Linear Model (GLM), and the same approach you used to model presence/absence data in the species distribution modelling workshop.

The CJS model uses information from capture histories where individuals were marked, not observed, and subsequently seen at a later date to estimate detection probabilities. For example, comparing the number of individuals with a capture history of 101 vs 111 is informative about detection probability on the second sampling event.

The most basic form of the model (the default) estimates constant survival and detection probabilities.

mod1 <- crm(sparrow) # capture-mark-recapture (cmr) model
mod1 # examine model and coefficient estimates
## 
## crm Model Summary
## 
## Npar :  2
## -2lnL:  2450.35
## AIC  :  2454.35
## 
## Beta
##                   Estimate
## Phi.(Intercept) 0.07109326
## p.(Intercept)   0.32242446
mod1 <- cjs.hessian(mod1) # refit model with precision estimates

As with a binomial GLM, these estimates are on the latent (logit) scale. We can transform them back to the data scale using the plogis() or predict() functions. The estimates on the data scale are also stored within the results section of the model under ‘reals’.

mod1$results$reals
## $Phi
##   occ  estimate
## 1   9 0.5177658
## 
## $p
##   occ estimate
## 1  10 0.579915
plogis(mod1$results$beta$Phi)
## (Intercept) 
##   0.5177658
plogis(mod1$results$beta$p)
## (Intercept) 
##    0.579915
predict(mod1, newdata=data.frame(sex = c('Female', 'Male')), se=T) # N.b. In this case, there are no groups or covariates in the model and so the 'newdata' argument is not used 
## $Phi
##   occ  estimate         se       lcl       ucl
## 1   1 0.5177658 0.01548384 0.4873893 0.5480116
## 
## $p
##   occ estimate         se       lcl       ucl
## 1   2 0.579915 0.02558621 0.5291095 0.6290816

The probability of surviving between capture events was therefore 0.518, and the probability of detecting an animal during a capture event was 0.580.

Unequal sampling intervals

This model assumes an equal time between each capture event. This assumption can be relaxed by including a vector of time intervals:

mod2 <- crm(sparrow, time.intervals = c(1,2,1,1,1,1,1,3,4))
mod2$results$reals
## $Phi
##   occ  estimate
## 1   9 0.6857959
## 
## $p
##   occ  estimate
## 1  10 0.5147669

Including static covariates

The islands in the meta-population are all different, and it is possible that the probability of capturing an individual differs between islands. We can test this by adding some additional complexity to our model and allowing the detection probability to vary between islands.

In the marked package, this is a three stage process: (1) data processing, (2) building the design matrix, (3) set up and execute candidate models. These steps are a little complex but we will use the built-in functions in marked to help us. You can type ?process.data or ?make.design.matrix to get more information on these functions. It is also helpful to examine the outputs of the functions to see what is happening. The outputs are lists, rather than dataframes. You can examine the different components of the lists using double square brackets or by naming them with the $ sign.

We can then specify the model formulation for the detection probability model, making p dependent on island. Finally, we run the CMR model using our newly processed data, our design matrix, and our model specification.

# specify model formulation: capture probability depends on island
p.island <- list(formula=~island) 

mod3 <- crm(sparrow.proc, 
            sparrow.ddl, 
            model.parameters = list(p = p.island), 
            accumulate=FALSE, hessian = TRUE)
mod3$results$reals

Does survival probability vary between the sexes?

To answer this question, we might want to test a few different model structures for both survival and detection components. We can make this easier by using a wrapper function like below.

sparrow.proc <- process.data(sparrow)
sparrow.ddl <- make.design.data(sparrow.proc)

fit.models <- function() {
  Phi.dot <- list(formula=~1) # constant survival
  Phi.sex <- list(formula=~sex) # survival differs between sexes
  Phi.island <- list(formula=~island) # survival differs between islands
  Phi.sex.island <- list(formula=~sex+island) # survival differs between sexes and islands
  p.dot <- list(formula=~1) # constant detection
  p.sex <- list(formula=~sex) # detection probability differs between sexes
  p.island <- list(formula=~island) # detection probability differs between islands
  p.sex.island <- list(formula=~sex+island) # detection probability differs between sexes and islands
  cml <- create.model.list(c("Phi","p"))
  results <- crm.wrapper(cml, data=sparrow.proc, ddl=sparrow.ddl,
                         external=FALSE, accumulate=FALSE, hessian=TRUE)
  return(results)
}

sparrow.models <- fit.models() # run function

The top model (with the lowest AIC value) includes a constant model for survival probability with detection probabilities differing among islands. In fact, there are a number of models with very similar AIC scores, indicating a similar level of support. However, AIC differences of less than 2 are not considered to be meaningfully different and so in this case we accept the simplest model - that with the fewest parameters. In this case, that is the top model. We can extract and plot the different detection probabilities as follows.

mod5 <- sparrow.models[[2]]

ggplot(mod5$results$reals$p, aes(island, estimate, ymin=lcl, ymax=ucl)) + 
  geom_errorbar(width=0.2) + geom_point() + ylim(0,1)

We can also extract the sex and island differences in survival from the similarly supported models and plot those to convince ourselves that there aren’t big differences.

mod6 <- sparrow.models[[10]]

Including time-varying covariates

We might want to test whether survival (or detection) probabilities differ depending on a factor that varies over time, such as some aspect of the weather. As an example, we will add a variable ‘cold’ to the design data (sparrow.ddl) and test whether it being an extra-cold winter affects survival.

sparrow.ddl$Phi$cold <- "Cold" # new column 
sparrow.ddl$Phi$cold[sparrow.ddl$Phi$time==2 | sparrow.ddl$Phi$time==5 | sparrow.ddl$Phi$time==8] <- "VeryCold" # very cold winters between capture events 2 and 3, 5 and 6, and 8 and 9

head(sparrow.ddl$Phi)
##   id occ time cohort age island    sex freq Time Cohort Age order     cold
## 1  1   1    1      9   0 Gjeroy Female    8    0      8   0     1     Cold
## 2  1   2    2      9   0 Gjeroy Female    8    1      8   0     2 VeryCold

Time varying survival and recapture probabilities

Finally, we can test whether survival and detection probabilities varied each year of the study period using the built-in time variable.

sparrow.proc <- process.data(sparrow)
sparrow.ddl <- make.design.data(sparrow.proc)

fit.models <- function() {
  Phi.dot <- list(formula=~1) # constant survival
  Phi.time <- list(formula=~time) # survival varies over time
  p.island <- list(formula=~island) # detection probability differs between islands
  p.time <- list(formula=~time) # detection probability varies over time
  p.island.time <- list(formula=~island+time) # detection probability varies over time
  cml <- create.model.list(c("Phi","p"))
  results <- crm.wrapper(cml, data=sparrow.proc, ddl=sparrow.ddl,
                         external=FALSE, accumulate=FALSE, hessian=TRUE)
  return(results)
}

sparrow.models <- fit.models() # run function 
sparrow.models # display model table

Goodness-of-fit tests (if you get this far…)

To test whether our data violate any of the basic assumptions of the CJS model, we can use the package R2ucare. This package contains functions to perform goodness-of-fit tests for CMR models. In particular, this package will test whether our data violate the ‘equal detection assumption’ or the ‘equal survival assumption’. First, we need to reformat the data into a matrix.

sparrow.gof <- sparrow$ch %>%
  strsplit('') %>%
  sapply(`[`) %>%
  t() %>%
  unlist() %>%
  as.numeric %>%
  matrix(nrow = nrow(sparrow))

R2ucare perfroms three tests, which are unhelpfully called Tests 1, 2 and 3.
* Test 1: the overall test. Overall, is there evidence that animals have equal detection probabilities and equal survival?
* Test 2: Does recapture depend on when an animal was first marked? (Tests the equal detection assumption)
* Test 3: Does marking affect survival? (Tests the equal survival assumption)

overall_CJS(sparrow.gof, rep(1,nrow(sparrow)))
##                          chi2 degree_of_freedom p_value
## Gof test for CJS model: 19.42                27   0.854

The p-value is not significant, meaning we fail to reject the null hypothesis. There is therefore no strong evidence for overall lack-of-fit.

If we found evidence of lack-of-fit, we would want to delve deeper to find out what the problem was. First, we can look at the equal detection assumption using Test 2, which has two components:
* Test 2 CT: Is there a difference in p at t+1 between those captured and not captured at t (when animals are known to be alive because are captured later in the study)?
* Test 2 CL: Is there a difference in the expected time of next recapture between individuals captured and not captured at t when animals are known to be alive?

test2ct <- test2ct(sparrow.gof, rep(1,nrow(sparrow)))

Finally, Test 3 which tests the equal survival assumption and also has two components:
* Test 3 SR: Do individuals with previous marks have different survival rates than first-time captures?
* Test 3 SM: For animals seen again, does when they are recaptured depend on whether they were marked on or before t?

test3sr <- test3sr(sparrow.gof, rep(1,nrow(sparrow)))

If your data violate the assumptions, you might need to increase the complexity of your model by adding age classes, including a time-varying individual covariate, or building a multistate or multievent model.
